^b@2mitche: OK -- 
I think I would like to discuss opener's rebids after a game-forcing 2 over 1 bid
Let's start by asking what responder has for a 2 over 1 response to 1@H or 1@S

a 2@C or 2@D bid promises a 4 card or longer suit and an opening bid
So with xx, KJx, AQxxx, Kxx you would bid 2@D over 1@S

If your hand were xx, KJx, KJxxx, Kxx, you would NOT bid 2@D (as you might in SA)
You would bid 1NT forcing

So opener has heard 2@C (let us say) over her 1@S opener
An immediate raise (of 2@C to 3@C) shows 4 card support 
If opener lacks 4 card support, he bids a 4-card or longer red suit. 

With no support or second suit to bid, opener's rebid should be 2NT with a balanced (5332) hand

Remember - you are not going to be passed out - so 2NT is still forcing
Most pairs play that 2NT shows any balanced hand, and could be stronger than the SA 2NT, which is a minimum hand
In any case, 2NT is natural 

If opener rebids his major, it usually is a 6 card suit (but it might also be a good 5 bagger).
Example KQJxx, Axx, x, Qxxx - opener starts 1@S, and responder bids 2@D
2NT is out (we aren't balanced)
and 3@C should be a better suit. 
So by default, you rebid 2@S|
